<subSubSection lastPageId="17" lastPageNumber="18" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="15.[189,1399,1792,1926]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">
<bibRefCitation author="Hayman" box="[189,475,1792,1819]" etAl="et al." firstAuthor="Hayman" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" pagination="1 - 105" refId="ref265860" refString="Hayman R. W., Misonne X. &amp; Verheyen W. N. 1966. The bats of the Congo and of Rwanda and Burundi. Annalen van het Koninklijk Museum voor Midden Afrika, Zoologische Wetenschappen, Ser. 8, 154: 1 - 105." type="journal article" year="1966">
Hayman 
<emphasis box="[295,353,1792,1818]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">et al.</emphasis>
(1966: 27
</bibRefCitation>
, map 13) reported two specimens belonging to this species, one from Thysville (= Mbanza-Ngungu) and one from Luluabourg (= Kananga). One additional specimen was reported by 
<bibRefCitation author="Bergmans" box="[189,452,1864,1890]" firstAuthor="Bergmans" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" pagination="89 - 153" refId="ref257278" refString="Bergmans W. 1989. Taxonomy and biogeography of African fruit bats (Mammalia, Megachiroptera). 2. The genera Micropteropus Matschie, 1899, Epomops Gray, 1870, Hypsignatus H. Allen, 1861, Nanonycteris, Matschie, 1899 and Plerotes Andersen, 1910. Beaufortia 39 (4): 89 - 153. Available from http: // www. repository. naturalis. nl / document / 548365 [accessed 29 Nov. 2017]." type="journal article" year="1989">Bergmans (1989: 101)</bibRefCitation>
from “Banana/Netonna”. Here, we add two further specimens from Luluabourg. All of these localities are relatively close to the Angolan border, where the 
<typeStatus box="[1068,1171,1899,1925]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">holotype</typeStatus>
was collected.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="15.[189,1398,1965,2027]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">
As indicated by 
<bibRefCitation author="Bergmans" box="[383,648,1965,1992]" firstAuthor="Bergmans" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" pagination="89 - 153" refId="ref257278" refString="Bergmans W. 1989. Taxonomy and biogeography of African fruit bats (Mammalia, Megachiroptera). 2. The genera Micropteropus Matschie, 1899, Epomops Gray, 1870, Hypsignatus H. Allen, 1861, Nanonycteris, Matschie, 1899 and Plerotes Andersen, 1910. Beaufortia 39 (4): 89 - 153. Available from http: // www. repository. naturalis. nl / document / 548365 [accessed 29 Nov. 2017]." type="journal article" year="1989">Bergmans (1989: 103)</bibRefCitation>
a number of these specimens were originally assigned to other, similar-sized epomophorine species (e.g., 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Peters" baseAuthorityYear="1867" box="[689,820,2001,2027]" class="Mammalia" family="Pteropodidae" genus="Micropteropus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="pusillus">
<emphasis box="[689,820,2001,2027]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">M. pusillus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
or 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Peters" authorityYear="1865" box="[862,1126,2001,2027]" class="Mammalia" family="Pteropodidae" genus="Epomophorus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="grandis">
<emphasis box="[862,1126,2001,2027]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">Epomophorus grandis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
[not yet reported from
</paragraph>
<caption ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3860089" ID-Zenodo-Dep="3860089" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3860089/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" startId="16.[189,232,1929,1955]" targetBox="[233,1353,305,1876]" targetPageId="16">
<paragraph blockId="16.[189,1398,1929,2027]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,268,1929,1956]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Fig. 5.</emphasis>
Distribution maps. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[506,561,1929,1955]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">A–B</emphasis>
. 
<taxonomicName authority="(Sundevall, 1846)" baseAuthorityName="Sundevall" baseAuthorityYear="1846" box="[578,1094,1930,1957]" class="Mammalia" family="Pteropodidae" genus="Epomophorus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="wahlbergi">
<emphasis box="[578,869,1930,1956]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Epomophorus wahlbergi</emphasis>
(Sundevall, 1846)
</taxonomicName>
. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1106,1163,1929,1955]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">C–D</emphasis>
. 
<taxonomicName authority="(Bocage, 1889)" baseAuthorityName="Bocage" baseAuthorityYear="1889" class="Mammalia" family="Pteropodidae" genus="Epomops" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="dobsonii">
<emphasis box="[1179,1398,1930,1956]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Epomops dobsonii</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Bocage" box="[197,365,1965,1991]" firstAuthor="Bocage" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" pagination="8 - 32" refId="ref257996" refString="Bocage J. V. B. 1889. Mammiferes d'Angola et du Congo. Jornal de Sciencas mathematicas, physicas e naturaes (2) 1 (1): 8 - 32. Available from https: // www. biodiversitylibrary. org / page / 4141036  page / 5 / mode / 1 up [accessed 29 Nov. 2017]." type="journal article" year="1889">Bocage, 1889</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[386,438,1965,1991]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">E–F</emphasis>
. 
<taxonomicName authority="(Tomes, 1860)" baseAuthorityName="Tomes" baseAuthorityYear="1860" box="[454,863,1965,1992]" class="Mammalia" family="Pteropodidae" genus="Epomops" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="franqueti">
<emphasis box="[454,679,1965,1991]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Epomops franqueti</emphasis>
(Tomes, 1860)
</taxonomicName>
. A, C, E. Distribution in the CRB area. B, D, F. Pan-African distribution.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="17.[189,1398,267,329]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">
CRB]) due to the careless preservation or examination of the soft palate. Therefore, we cannot exclude that some of the specimens reported here as 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Peters" baseAuthorityYear="1867" box="[709,839,303,329]" class="Mammalia" family="Pteropodidae" genus="Micropteropus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="pusillus">
<emphasis box="[709,839,303,329]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">M. pusillus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
might belong to the current species.
</paragraph>
